<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-079-292 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 147 813</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 19 1991 v25 n33 p4(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer services tax unwelcome in Pa. (Pennsylvania law applyingsales tax to computer services)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilder, Clinton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Both vendors and users are very unhappy with a new Pennsylvanialaw that will increase the cost of computer services by extendingthe state's six percent sales tax to cover a wide array ofcomputer services.andP;  The bill puts a sales tax on six differentcategories of computer services: processing, programming,information retrieval, systems design, facilities management andother services including software installation, databaseconsulting and tape conversion.andP;  Service vendors say the tax willhurt their competitive position against out of state vendors.andO;Pennsylvania companies that have outsourced information systemsoperations to locally based vendors could also be negativelyaffected.andP;  Pennsylvania has a $3 billion state budget deficit, andthe tax on computer services is part of a complete tax packagethat also taxes pizza delivery, pest control and lawn careservices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer ServicesTaxLegislationPennsylvania.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Contradiction in tax. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>